[src:manova/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] is the unbiased **pooled covariance matrix** estimate (an extension of pooled variance).
[src:manova/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] In the two-variable case, the formula simplifies nicely allowing appreciation of how the correlation, $\rho$ , between the variables affects $t^{2}$ .
[src:manova/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] If the differences are of opposite sign $t^{2}$ becomes larger as $\rho$ becomes more positive.
[src:manova/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] A univariate special case can be found in Welch's t-test.
[src:manova/hotelling-s-t-squared-distribution] More robust and powerful tests than the Hotelling's two-sample test have been proposed in the literature, see for example the interpoint distance based tests which can be applied also when the number of variables is comparable with, or even larger than, the number of subjects.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] In statistics, **multivariate analysis of variance** (**MANOVA**) is a procedure for comparing multivariate sample means.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] As a multivariate procedure, it is used when there are two or more dependent variables, and is often followed by significance tests involving individual dependent variables separately.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Without relation to the image, the dependent variables may be k life satisfactions scores measured at sequential time points and p job satisfaction scores measured at sequential time points.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] In this case there are k+p dependent variables whose linear combination follows a multivariate normal distribution, multivariate variance-covariance matrix homogeneity, and linear relationship, no multicollinearity, and each without outliers.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] MANOVA is a generalized form of univariate analysis of variance (ANOVA), although, unlike univariate ANOVA, it uses the covariance between outcome variables in testing the statistical significance of the mean differences.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Where sums of squares appear in univariate analysis of variance, in multivariate analysis of variance certain positive-definite matrices appear.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] The diagonal entries are the same kinds of sums of squares that appear in univariate ANOVA.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] The off-diagonal entries are corresponding sums of products.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Under normality assumptions about error distributions, the counterpart of the sum of squares due to error has a Wishart distribution.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Then the matrix ${\textstyle S_{\text{model}}:=({\hat {Y}}-{\bar {Y}})^{T}({\hat {Y}}-{\bar {Y}})}$ is a generalization of the sum of squares explained by the group, and ${\textstyle S_{\text{res}}:=(Y-{\hat {Y}})^{T}(Y-{\hat {Y}})}$ is a generalization of the residual sum of squares.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Note that alternatively one could also speak about covariances when the abovementioned matrices are scaled by 1/(n-1) since the subsequent test statistics do not change by multiplying ${\textstyle S_{\text{model}}}$ and ${\textstyle S_{\text{res}}}$ by the same non-zero constant.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Discussion continues over the merits of each, although the greatest root leads only to a bound on significance which is not generally of practical interest.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] A further complication is that, except for the Roy's greatest root, the distribution of these statistics under the null hypothesis is not straightforward and can only be approximated except in a few low-dimensional cases.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] An algorithm for the distribution of the Roy's largest root under the null hypothesis was derived in while the distribution under the alternative is studied in.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] The best-known approximation for Wilks' lambda was derived by C.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] In the case of two groups, all the statistics are equivalent and the test reduces to Hotelling's T-square.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] One can also test if there is a group effect after adjusting for covariates.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Then ${\textstyle S_{\text{model}}}$ are the additional sum of squares explained by adding the grouping information and ${\textstyle S_{\text{res}}}$ is the residual sum of squares of the model containing the grouping and the covariates.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] Note that in case of unbalanced data, the order of adding the covariates matters.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] MANOVA's power is affected by the correlations of the dependent variables and by the effect sizes associated with those variables.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis-of-variance] For example, when there are two groups and two dependent variables, MANOVA's power is lowest when the correlation equals the ratio of the smaller to the larger standardized effect size.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Multivariate analysis can be complicated by the desire to include physics-based analysis to calculate the effects of variables for a hierarchical "system-of-systems".
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Often, studies that wish to use multivariate analysis are stalled by the dimensionality of the problem.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] These concerns are often eased through the use of surrogate models, highly accurate approximations of the physics-based code.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Since surrogate models take the form of an equation, they can be evaluated very quickly.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] This becomes an enabler for large-scale MVA studies: while a Monte Carlo simulation across the design space is difficult with physics-based codes, it becomes trivial when evaluating surrogate models, which often take the form of response-surface equations.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Multivariate regression attempts to determine a formula that can describe how elements in a vector of variables respond simultaneously to changes in others.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] For linear relations, regression analyses here are based on forms of the general linear model.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Some suggest that multivariate regression is distinct from multivariable regression, however, that is debated and not consistently true across scientific fields.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Principal components analysis (PCA) creates a new set of orthogonal variables that contain the same information as the original set.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] It rotates the axes of variation to give a new set of orthogonal axes, ordered so that they summarize decreasing proportions of the variation.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Factor analysis is similar to PCA but allows the user to extract a specified number of synthetic variables, fewer than the original set, leaving the remaining unexplained variation as error.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] The extracted variables are known as latent variables or factors; each one may be supposed to account for covariation in a group of observed variables.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Canonical correlation analysis finds linear relationships among two sets of variables; it is the generalised (i.e. canonical) version of bivariate correlation.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Redundancy analysis (RDA) is similar to canonical correlation analysis but allows the user to derive a specified number of synthetic variables from one set of (independent) variables that explain as much variance as possible in another (independent) set.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] It is a multivariate analogue of regression.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Correspondence analysis (CA), or reciprocal averaging, finds (like PCA) a set of synthetic variables that summarise the original set.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] The underlying model assumes chi-squared dissimilarities among records (cases).
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Canonical (or "constrained") correspondence analysis (CCA) for summarising the joint variation in two sets of variables (like redundancy analysis); combination of correspondence analysis and multivariate regression analysis.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Multidimensional scaling comprises various algorithms to determine a set of synthetic variables that best represent the pairwise distances between records.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] The original method is principal coordinates analysis (PCoA; based on PCA).
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Discriminant analysis, or canonical variate analysis, attempts to establish whether a set of variables can be used to distinguish between two or more groups of cases.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) computes a linear predictor from two sets of normally distributed data to allow for classification of new observations.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Clustering systems assign objects into groups (called clusters) so that objects (cases) from the same cluster are more similar to each other than objects from different clusters.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Recursive partitioning creates a decision tree that attempts to correctly classify members of the population based on a dichotomous dependent variable.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Artificial neural networks extend regression and clustering methods to non-linear multivariate models.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Statistical graphics such as tours, parallel coordinate plots, scatterplot matrices can be used to explore multivariate data.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Simultaneous equations models involve more than one regression equation, with different dependent variables, estimated together.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Vector autoregression involves simultaneous regressions of various time series variables on their own and each other's lagged values.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Principal response curves analysis (PRC) is a method based on RDA that allows the user to focus on treatment effects over time by correcting for changes in control treatments over time.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] It is very common that in an experimentally acquired set of data the values of some components of a given data point are missing.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Rather than discarding the whole data point, it is common to "fill in" values for the missing components, a process called "imputation".
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] There is a set of probability distributions used in multivariate analyses that play a similar role to the corresponding set of distributions that are used in univariate analysis when the normal distribution is appropriate to a dataset.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] The Inverse-Wishart distribution is important in Bayesian inference, for example in Bayesian multivariate linear regression.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Additionally, Hotelling's T-squared distribution is a multivariate distribution, generalising Student's t-distribution, that is used in multivariate hypothesis testing.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Rao made significant contributions to multivariate statistical theory throughout his career, particularly in the mid-20th century.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] One of his key works is the book titled "Advanced Statistical Methods in Biometric Research," published in 1952.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] This work laid the foundation for many concepts in multivariate statistics.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] Anderson's 1958 textbook,*An Introduction to Multivariate Statistical Analysis*, educated a generation of theorists and applied statisticians; Anderson's book emphasizes hypothesis testing via likelihood ratio tests and the properties of power functions: admissibility, unbiasedness and monotonicity.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] MVA was formerly discussed solely in the context of statistical theories, due to the size and complexity of underlying datasets and its high computational consumption.
[src:manova/multivariate-analysis] With the dramatic growth of computational power, MVA now plays an increasingly important role in data analysis and has wide application in Omics fields.
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] In statistics, **Wilks' lambda distribution** (named for Samuel S.
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] Wilks), is a probability distribution used in multivariate hypothesis testing, especially with regard to the likelihood-ratio test and multivariate analysis of variance (MANOVA).
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] In the context of likelihood-ratio tests *m* is typically the error degrees of freedom, and *n* is the hypothesis degrees of freedom, so that $n+m$ is the total degrees of freedom.
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] Computations or tables of the Wilks' distribution for higher dimensions are not readily available and one usually resorts to approximations.
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] Another approximation is attributed to C.
[src:manova/wilks-s-lambda-distribution] As such it can be regarded as a multivariate generalization of the beta distribution.
